  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the best budget-friendly wines under $15 for chicken dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Excellent value options include Spanish Albariño ($10-12), Portuguese Vinho Verde ($8-10), and Côtes du Rhône rouge ($12-15) which offer restaurant-quality pairings without breaking the bank. For white wines, look for Grüner Veltliner from Austria or Vermentino from Italy, both typically under $15 and incredibly food-friendly. These wines provide complexity and character that enhance chicken dishes while remaining accessible for everyday dining.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair red wine with chicken, and when does it work best?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—red wine pairs excellently with chicken when the preparation is robust enough to match the wine's intensity. Light to medium-bodied reds like Pinot Noir, Gamay, or Dolcetto work beautifully with roasted chicken, especially with herbs or garlic. For grilled, barbecued, or heavily spiced chicken dishes, you can even use fuller reds like Malbec or Tempranillo, as the char and bold flavors create enough weight to balance the wine.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing wine for chicken?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is automatically defaulting to white wine without considering the preparation method and seasonings. While the "white wine with white meat" rule is a good starting point, it ignores how cooking techniques and sauces transform the dish's flavor profile. A heavily seasoned jerk chicken or coq au vin requires completely different wine considerations than a simple poached breast, and sticking rigidly to white wines can result in mismatched pairings.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How do I adjust my wine choice for spicy chicken dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">For spicy chicken preparations, choose wines with lower alcohol (under 13%), slight sweetness, and good acidity to cool the palate and cleanse between bites. German Riesling, Gewürztraminer, or even a chilled Beaujolais work exceptionally well with buffalo chicken or curry-spiced dishes. Avoid high-tannin reds and high-alcohol wines, as they intensify the heat sensation rather than providing relief.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine at different temperatures depending on the chicken dish?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Yes, temperature plays a crucial role in the pairing success. Serve white wines slightly warmer (50-55°F) with rich, creamy chicken dishes to allow their full flavor complexity to emerge, while keeping them cooler (45-50°F) for lighter preparations. Light red wines should be served slightly chilled (60-65°F) with chicken to prevent the alcohol from overwhelming the delicate meat, especially during warmer weather or with grilled preparations.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good non-alcoholic alternatives that pair similarly with chicken?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Quality non-alcoholic wines like Ariel Chardonnay or Fre White Zinfandel maintain similar flavor profiles and acidity levels that complement chicken dishes effectively. For a different approach, try premium sparkling grape juice, kombucha with fruity notes, or even well-crafted non-alcoholic beer with wheat or citrus characteristics. The key is finding beverages with sufficient acidity and complexity to enhance rather than compete with the chicken's flavors.</p>
